const POEM_A1 = `Storm Over Lindisfarne

The sea returns what it has taken —
salt-bleached timber, fractured shell,
the ribcage of a boat that once
held men who thought they knew the swell.

The priory stands in silhouette,
its arches open to the wind
like mouths that stopped mid-prayer
when the raiders came, and sinned.

I walk the causeway as the tide
reclaims the sand on either side,
and think of all the faiths we build
on ground the water will not hide.`

const POEM_A1_AUTHOR = 'Original composition — Nature and history'

const POEM_A2 = `The Photographer's Daughter

My father kept the world in boxes —
silver halide, fixed in time,
each frame a careful theft of light
from someone else's paradigm.

I learned to smile by watching negatives,
where shadows wore the brighter face
and all the light was rendered dark
and darkness held the truest grace.

He photographed me every year
against the same white garden wall.
I grew. The wall did not. The vine
crept further. That was all.

The last print shows me leaving —
half-turned, blurred, already gone.
He kept it, underexposed,
the brightest thing he'd ever done.`

const POEM_A2_AUTHOR = 'Original composition — Memory and identity'

const POEM_A3 = `Night Shift

The vending machine hums its one fluorescent hymn
to no one. Corridors stretch and yawn.
I push a trolley loaded with the quiet needs
of people balanced between dusk and dawn.

Ward Six is sleeping. Ward Seven pretends.
In Ward Eight, Mrs Kohli stares at the ceiling
and tells me about Lahore in 1962 —
the jasmine, the heat, a particular feeling

she cannot translate. I change her water.
I check her chart. I write the numbers down.
Outside, the car park holds its breath.
Somewhere, a siren stitches up the town.

I clock off into a sky the colour of a bruise.
The sun comes up. I close my eyes.
The world divides so neatly into those
who sleep at night, and those who supervise.`

const POEM_A3_AUTHOR = 'Original composition — Work and modern life'

const POEM_A4 = `Inheritance

My mother's hands were maps of labour —
cracked across the knuckle line,
stained with soil from someone else's garden,
smelling faintly of turpentine.

She cleaned the houses of the wealthy,
polished surfaces she'd never own,
arranged their cut flowers in crystal vases,
walked home through the dark alone.

I hold a pen. She held a mop.
The distance between us is a single generation
and a universe. She wanted more for me.
I wanted her. There is no equation

that balances ambition against loss,
no formula for what it costs to rise.
I write these words with hands that never laboured,
and that is both the gift and the disguise.`

const POEM_A4_AUTHOR = 'Original composition — Social class and family'

const POEM_A5 = `The Border

They drew a line across the earth
and called it necessary —
a clean incision, cartographic,
ordinary, temporary.

That was sixty years ago.
The line became a wall, the wall
became a fact, the fact became
the only truth the children knew at all.

On this side: language, bread, a flag.
On that side: language, bread, a flag.
The difference? A syllable.
A colour. An accent on the second syllable.

My grandmother remembers crossing freely.
My mother remembers crossing once.
I have never crossed. The wall
is older now than anyone's

memory of what it separated.
We press our palms against the stone
and feel, or imagine that we feel,
a warmth that is not quite our own.`

