const UNSEEN_POEM_01 = `The Allotment in November

Everything is ending and beginning here.
The runner beans have blackened on their canes,
the courgette leaves have turned to yellow rags
and slug-lace stitches silver through the rain.

My father's plot. Now mine. The shed still holds
his tobacco tin of carefully saved seed,
his handwriting on each brown envelope —
Broad Windsor, Scarlet Emperor — a creed

of patience I am only now beginning
to decode. He never rushed. He watched
the sky the way a sailor watches: reading
pressure, wind, the light. He watched and notched

each season into memory, and planted
not for harvest but for faith — the quiet trust
that what you bury in the dark will rise,
that sweetness can be conjured out of dust.`

