              'Grade 6-7': 'Shakespeare dramatises Macbeth\'s psychological disintegration through the extended conceit of the phantom dagger. The soliloquy\'s opening interrogative, "Is this a dagger which I see before me," establishes a radical epistemological crisis: Macbeth can no longer trust the evidence of his senses. The imperative "Come, let me clutch thee" is desperate and futile, directed at an absence, which stages the futility of his desire to control what is already beyond control. The phrase "a false creation / Proceeding from the heat-oppressed brain" is a moment of terrifying lucidity within the hallucination — Macbeth diagnoses his own madness even as he succumbs to it. The blood that materialises on the blade ("gouts of blood, / Which was not so before") enacts a physical manifestation of guilt, the murder bleeding backwards in time to stain the instrument before the act. Shakespeare then widens the lens from the psychological to the cosmic: "Now o\'er the one half-world / Nature seems dead" aligns Macbeth\'s crime with the suspension of natural order, a theme central to the play\'s moral architecture. The classical allusion to Tarquin — a rapist king — deliberately conflates tyranny with violation, foreshadowing the political rape of Scotland that Macbeth\'s regicide will constitute.',
