              'Grade 4-5': 'Both poems explore the relationship between people and the natural world but in different ways. In "Storm Over Lindisfarne," the poet describes a coastal landscape with powerful natural imagery like "salt-bleached timber" and "fractured shell." The sea is presented as a force that takes and returns things, suggesting nature is more powerful than humans. The priory\'s arches are "open to the wind / like mouths that stopped mid-prayer," which is a simile showing how nature has outlasted human faith. In "Inheritance," the natural world is connected to social class. The mother works in other people\'s gardens, creating a contrast between those who own nature (the wealthy with their gardens) and those who labour in it. The poet uses the metaphor of hands as "maps of labour" to connect the body to work. Both poems suggest that nature outlasts human concerns — the sea erodes the priory, and the garden outlasts the mother — but "Lindisfarne" treats nature with awe while "Inheritance" treats it as a site of inequality.',
              'Grade 6-7': 'Both poets use the natural world as a lens through which to examine human impermanence and inherited meaning, though their tonal registers differ significantly. In "Storm Over Lindisfarne," nature is presented as an agent of historical erasure. The opening line — "The sea returns what it has taken" — establishes the ocean as a cyclical force that operates outside human time. The listed objects ("salt-bleached timber, fractured shell, / the ribcage of a boat") are remnants of human activity reduced to elemental materials, the "ribcage" metaphor animalising the boat and suggesting the sea consumes its victims. The priory, a monument to faith, is described with its arches "open to the wind / like mouths that stopped mid-prayer" — a devastating simile that captures the moment faith was interrupted by violence (the Viking raids) and never resumed. The final stanza\'s meditation on "faiths we build / on ground the water will not hide" universalises this: all human constructions — religious, political, emotional — are temporary. In "Inheritance," nature is mediated through labour and class. The mother\'s hands are "stained with soil from someone else\'s garden" — the possessive "someone else\'s" is politically charged, exposing how nature itself is privatised and access to it stratified by wealth. The domestic natural imagery (cut flowers, crystal vases) is aestheticised and controlled, contrasted with the raw physicality of the mother\'s labour. Structurally, "Lindisfarne" uses the walk along the causeway as a physical and meditative journey, with the closing tide creating urgency, while "Inheritance" uses the generational contrast (mop/pen) as its structural spine. Both poems conclude with irresolution: "Lindisfarne" with the acknowledgement that faith is built on unstable ground, "Inheritance" with the paradox that upward mobility is "both the gift and the disguise."',
              'Grade 8-9': 'These poems deploy the natural world in fundamentally different epistemological registers — as metaphysical testament and as socioeconomic terrain — yet converge in their recognition that the relationship between people and nature is always mediated by time, loss, and inherited meaning. "Storm Over Lindisfarne" operates in the elegiac tradition, positioning the speaker as a solitary figure reading landscape as palimpsest. The sea is characterised by paradox: it simultaneously destroys and preserves, "returns what it has taken" in altered form. The listed detritus occupies a liminal category between nature and culture — timber and shells are natural materials shaped by human use, now reclaimed by elemental process. The "ribcage of a boat" is the poem\'s most compressed image, collapsing the distinction between vessel and body, suggesting that all human making is ultimately organic and therefore subject to organic decay. The priory\'s arches function architecturally as both ruin and frame, "open to the wind" in a state of permanent vulnerability. The simile "like mouths that stopped mid-prayer" is historically precise (alluding to Lindisfarne\'s Viking destruction in 793) but resonates metaphysically: prayer is the human attempt to transcend nature, and its interruption by natural violence encapsulates the poem\'s central tension. The causeway, submerged twice daily, becomes the poem\'s controlling metaphor for conditional access — to place, to meaning, to faith. "Inheritance" reconfigures the nature-human relationship through the lens of material conditions. The mother\'s hands as "maps of labour" draw on cartographic imagery to suggest her body is a territory colonised by work. The soil under her nails is "someone else\'s" — a phrase that transforms horticulture into property relations and positions the mother as alienated from the natural world she tends. The structural pivot at "I hold a pen. She held a mop" uses the brutal simplicity of monosyllables and parallel syntax to stage class transformation as a series of substitutions. The final admission that the speaker\'s unlaboured hands are "both the gift and the disguise" is a sophisticated recognition that social mobility requires the erasure of its own origins — the pen, unlike the mop, leaves no physical trace on the body. Both poems ultimately argue that nature is never experienced neutrally: it is always filtered through the accumulated weight of history (Lindisfarne) or the structural conditions of class (Inheritance), and any attempt to encounter it directly is itself a form of inherited belief.',
