            id: 'ocr-lit-01-q3a',
            questionNumber: 4,
            questionText: 'Read the poem below.\n\nHow does the poet present ideas about memory and place?\n\nYou should consider the poet\'s use of language, form, and structure.\n\n(24 marks)',
            marks: 24,
            suggestedTimeMinutes: 20,
            questionType: 'analysis',
            extract: UNSEEN_POEM_01,
            extractSource: UNSEEN_POEM_01_AUTHOR,
            modelAnswers: {
              'Grade 4-5': 'The poet presents memory and place as connected through the allotment, which the speaker has inherited from their father. The physical place holds memories — the "tobacco tin of carefully saved seed" is both a real object and a symbol of the father\'s careful nature. The father\'s handwriting on the seed envelopes ("Broad Windsor, Scarlet Emperor") makes his presence feel physical and ongoing. The poet uses natural imagery to suggest that memory, like seeds, can lie dormant and then grow: "what you bury in the dark will rise." The allotment is described as a place where "everything is ending and beginning," which suggests that memory is cyclical, like the seasons. The father\'s patience is presented as something the speaker is "only now beginning / to decode," suggesting that understanding comes slowly through returning to the same place.',
              'Grade 6-7': 'The poet intertwines memory and place by making the allotment a site where the dead continue to instruct the living. The opening line — "Everything is ending and beginning here" — establishes the allotment as a space of simultaneous decay and renewal, with the deictic "here" anchoring the poem in physical specificity. The autumnal imagery ("blackened" beans, "yellow rags" of courgette leaves) presents natural decomposition, yet the poem resists elegy through its insistence on continuity. The father\'s preserved seeds function as a material archive: "Broad Windsor, Scarlet Emperor" are both varietal names and imperatives, as though the father is still issuing instructions from beyond death. The enjambment across "a creed / of patience" is structurally significant — the line break enacts the pause that patience requires, and the word "creed" elevates gardening to a spiritual practice. The father "watched / the sky the way a sailor watches" — a simile that connects agricultural observation to navigation, suggesting that tending the earth requires the same attentiveness as reading the sea. The final couplet\'s assertion that the father "planted / not for harvest but for faith" reframes gardening as an existential act. The poem\'s form — four quatrains with half-rhymes — enacts the regularity and gentle variation of seasonal cycles.',
              'Grade 8-9': 'The poem constructs an epistemology of inherited knowledge in which place is the medium through which the dead transmit understanding to the living. The allotment is simultaneously literal and figurative — a physical site of cultivation and a metaphor for the slow, patient work of grief and learning. The opening paradox ("Everything is ending and beginning here") collapses the temporal binary, positioning the allotment as a space where entropy and genesis coexist. The decaying vegetables are rendered with precise, unglamorous imagery ("blackened," "yellow rags," "slug-lace") that refuses to sentimentalise nature, yet the compound neologism "slug-lace" introduces unexpected delicacy, as though even decay has its own aesthetic logic. The father\'s preserved seeds constitute a secular scripture — his handwriting on "each brown envelope" transforms horticultural record-keeping into calligraphy, each varietal name ("Broad Windsor, Scarlet Emperor") carrying the weight of a private language the speaker must learn to read. The simile comparing the father to a sailor is richly apt: both read natural signs to navigate uncertainty, and both operate within systems larger than themselves. The pivotal enjambment "planted / not for harvest but for faith" disrupts the expected purpose of agriculture (production) and substitutes a metaphysical one (belief). The final image — "sweetness can be conjured out of dust" — operates on multiple registers: literal (seeds germinating in soil), biblical (dust-to-dust), and alchemical (base matter transformed). The poem\'s form, with its steady quatrains and measured enjambments, formally embodies the patience it celebrates.',
            },
